statement.p:
The first step for solving each equation below is incorrect. Replace it with the correct step.






\begin{aligned}
    6(5^{3t})\amp=20\\
    \color{gray}{(\log 6)(\log 5^{3t})}\amp=\color{gray}{\log {20}}\amp\amp \blert{\text{(Wrong!)}}
    \end{aligned}

Instead, the first step should be





 5^{3t} = \frac{20}{6}




 18t =\log_5 20




 30^{3t}=20








\begin{aligned}
    t \log 8\amp=\log{53}\\
    \color{gray}{t}\amp=\color{gray}{\log {\dfrac{53}{8}}}\amp\amp \blert{\text{(Wrong!)}}
    \end{aligned}

Instead, the first step should be





 t=\frac{53}{8}




 t = 8^{53}




 t = \frac{\log 53}{\log 8}








\begin{aligned}
    12(10)^{-0.06t}\amp=192\\
    \color{gray}{120^{-0.06t}}\amp=\color{gray}{192}\amp\amp \blert{\text{(Wrong!)}}
    \end{aligned}

Instead, the first step should be





 (\log 12)\left(\log 10^{-0.06t}\right)=\log 192




 10^{-0.72t} = 192




 10^{-0.06t} = \frac{192}{12}








\begin{aligned}
    \log x +\log {(x-2)}\amp=3 \\
    \color{gray}{x + (x-2)}\amp=\color{gray}{10^3}\amp\amp \blert{\text{(Wrong!)}}
    \end{aligned}

Instead, the first step should be





 \log 2x-2=3




 \log{(x(x-2))} = 3




 \log x + \log x - \log 2 = 3

